"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
The Lingones and Treveri, who had supported Verginius, are meant.
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1B*.html#53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.53 f.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
The district along the Rhine was divided for administrative and military purposes into Upper Germany and Lower Germany. Upper Germany extended on both sides of the Rhine from Vindonissa (Windisch, near Lake Constance) to Mogontiacum (Mainz); Lower Germany from Mogontiacum to the North Sea, but included little territory on the east bank of the Rhine. Usually there were four legions in each district; but at this time there were only three in Upper Germany.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
Aulus Vitellius had enjoyed the favour of Caligula, Claudius, and Nero in turn. In 48 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> he had been consul ordinarius with L. Vipstanus Poblicola;<!-- sic --> he had been proconsul of Africa, apparently in 60‑61, and in the following year he served in the same province as <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">legatus</SPAN> of his brother,


<A ID="p17x"></A> who was then governor. He was a member of most of the important priesthoods, and also held the office of commissioner of public works at Rome. Tacitus characterizes him below,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/2B*.html#86
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.86</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
The legions here referred to had been withdrawn on account of Vindex's revolt.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
Licinius Mucianus had been consul under Nero, and in 67 was appointed governor of Syria. After Vespasian claimed the imperial power Mucianus became his strongest supporter; the details are given below,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/home.html#H.2
	"TARGET="index"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Books <SPAN CLASS="small">II‑IV</SPAN></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref25
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
Titus Flavius Vespasianus was born at Reate in 9 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> Up to the present he had spent his life as a soldier and administrator in Thrace, Crete, Germany, and Britain; he had been aedile in 38, praetor in 40, and consul in 51 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>; and in 66 he was appointed general by Nero to conduct the war against the Jews.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
On the position and importance of Egypt, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2C*.html#59
	"TARGET="Tacitus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Tacitus,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Ann.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.59</A>: "For Augustus had made it one of the secret principles of his power to keep Egypt to himself and not to allow senators or eminent knights to enter it without his permission. His purpose was to save Italy from the danger of being starved; indeed Italy was at the mercy of any man who once got control of Egypt, for the province is the key


<A ID="p21x"></A>to both sea and land; and a small force there could resist large armies."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note27" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref27
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">27</A>
Icelus had hurried from Rome to Galba in Spain with the news of Nero's death, and had been rewarded the gold ring and the privilege of wearing the narrow purple stripe (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">angustus clavus</SPAN>) on his tunic, that were prerogatives of the equestrian order. He then became one of Galba's chief advisers; he was later executed by Otho.
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Galba*.html#7
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plut. <I>Galba</I>, 7</A>, Suet. <I>Galba</I>, <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Galba*.html#14
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A>, <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Galba*.html#22
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note28" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref28
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">28</A>
M. Salvius Otho, born 32 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>, had governed Lusitania well for ten years (59‑68 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>) under Nero, but had promptly joined Galba's cause and had accompanied him to Rome. For a somewhat different account of his relation to Poppaea, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/13B*.html#45
	"TARGET="Tacitus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Tacitus,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Ann.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XIII</SPAN>.45</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note29" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">29</A>
The expression "imperial comitia" is ironical, in imitation of "consular comitia," etc., which described the ordinary elections. The date of the adoption was January 10.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note30" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref30
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">30</A>
Piso, born 38 <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN>, was long an exile under Nero
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.48)</A>, and therefore had held no civil offices in the State. His father, mother, and one brother had been put to death by Claudius, a second brother killed by Nero.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note31" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>
To give validity to the adoption of a mature person the approval of the curiae and of the pontifices was necessary. The curiate assembly had lost its political power in 286 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, but it was still represented by thirty lictors, assembled by the pontifices. Galba, as pontifex maximus, dispensed with the usual forms.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note32" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref32
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">32</A>
According to the primitive method of raising levies.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note33" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref33
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">33</A>
A sum roughly equivalent to $100,000,000 of our money, but the vastly greater value of money in antiquity must be taken into account to arrive at a just comparison.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note34" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref34
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">34</A>
On Tigellinus, see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1B*.html#72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.72
	</A>
below.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">speculatores</SPAN> were picked men, chosen from the praetorians, who formed the bodyguard of the emperor.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">miliarium aureum</SPAN> was a column, covered with gilt-bronze, erected by Augustus, on which were engraved the names of the chief cities of the empire and their distances from Rome.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
This was on the west side of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Campus Agrippae</SPAN>, a piazza laid out by Agrippa on the Campus Martius, and finished and dedicated by Augustus in 7 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
This building, which held the archives and offices of the censors, had been restored by Asinius Pollio, who in 39 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<A ID="p55x"></A> established in it the first public library at Rome. It was apparently on or near the site on which Trajan later built his forum.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. 6
	</A>
above.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
https://www.curculio.org/Juvenal/s10.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Juvenal\'s 10th Satire'+Lat2+LatSearch+'perniciosa</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Juvenal <SPAN CLASS="small">X</SPAN>.54‑77</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Galba*.html#19
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Suet. <I>Galba</I>, 19</A>, for a different account.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
Favourite freedmen of Nero, whose inclination indulged their greed.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
Vologaesus became king of the Parthians in the reign of Claudius; Pacorus was king of Media, now apparently subject to the Parthians. <I>Cf.</I> <I>Annals</I>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/12A*.html
	"TARGET="Tacitus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Tacitus,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XII</SPAN>
	</A>
and <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/15A*.html
	"TARGET="Tacitus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Tacitus,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><SPAN CLASS="small">XV</SPAN></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
At this time an enclosed spot in the forum.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
Both the consuls, Galba and Vinius, were now dead.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus had married the emperor Claudius's daughter Antonia in 41, but within six years he was put to death. Marcus Licinius Crassus Frugi was charged with treason by the notorious Marcus Aquilius Regulus and executed between 66 and 68. <I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/4B*.html#42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.42</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
Under the second triumvirate in 43 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> <I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/47*.html#7.4
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,190)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Dio C. <SPAN CLASS="small">XLVII</SPAN>.7</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
That is, the emperor's cupidity disregarded the provisions of the will.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
According to
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Galba*.html#28
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Galba</I> 28</A>, this office was performed by the famous Helvidius Priscus.



